article.description:
Rebekkah Brunson had 11 points and 11 rebounds to lead the Monarchs over the Lynx
61-52 on Saturday night.
article.headline: Monarchs rule over Lynx in final regular-season game
article.linkText: Monarchs rule over Lynx in final regular-season game
article.story:
MINNEAPOLIS (AP) -- Despite having nothing to gain, the
Sacramento Monarchs played like the season was on the line.

Rebekkah Brunson had 11 points and 11 rebounds to lead
Sacramento over the Minnesota Lynx 61-52 in the regular season
finale for both teams.

The Monarchs already had the top seed in the Western Conference
locked up.

"The goal tonight was to keep our rhythm, keep going and keep
fighting," head coach John Whisenant said. "But we definitely
wanted some of our key starters to play less minutes."

"We are a team with a lot of energy and our rebounding and
defense has been the key like it was tonight," Brunson said. "We
come together as a group to get it done."

Yolanda Griffith had 17 points and seven rebounds in just 25
minutes for Sacramento (25-9), which will open the playoffs at Los
Angeles.

"I think this will be a good matchup for us," Brunson said of
the Sparks. "It will be intense."

Nicole Ohlde scored 18 points for the Lynx (14-20), who lost the
last four games of the season and will miss the playoffs for the
first time in three years.

"It's definitely disappointing," Ohlde said, reflecting on the
season. "We had a goal this year of going to the playoffs and
advancing. It's got to be motivation for us in the offseason."

Trailing 26-17 at halftime, Minnesota tied the score at 36-36
with 10:42 left. Ohlde led the charge, scoring nine points during a
19-10 run.

The score was tied again at 42 before Sacramento veterans
Griffith and Ticha Penicheiro took over.

Penicheiro scored five straight points and Griffith had six for
the Monarchs as they took a 55-50 lead with 1 minute left. The Lynx
could not get any closer the rest of the way.

The Monarchs used a stifling fullcourt press to force 10
turnovers and hold Minnesota to 21.4 percent shooting (6-for-28) in
the first half. The Lynx were scoreless from 11:59 to 7:12, and
then again for the last 5:28 of the half.

Sacramento shot just 13-for-25 from the foul line and
outrebounded Minnesota 39-27.
